- "Top 3 most versioned documents" are the documents with the highest number of versions;
- "Categories and labels" provide additional context and classification for the documents.

- 'Analysts' are users with a specific role in the system;
- 'Documents' are categorized and each category has a unique identifier;
- 'Access logs' track which documents are accessed by which users;
- 'Top 3 categories' are determined by the number of documents accessed within each category.

- 'Active' refers to the status of the document being currently in use or not archived;
- 'First category' refers to the category with ID 1;
- 'Introductory/Generic' is a label name that describes the type of content in the document.

- 'Active documents' are those whose status is set to 'active';
- 'Content' refers to the textual or digital information contained within the document;
- 'Accessed more than once' means the document has been viewed or accessed by users more than a single time;
- 'Non-empty content' indicates that the document has some form of information and is not blank.

- 'Introductory/Generic' refers to documents that are typically used as general introductions or overviews;
- 'Initial version' indicates the first version of the document;
- 'Accessed more frequently than the average' means the document's access count is above the mean access count of all documents.

